# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aleutian-islands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] The **180th meridian** or **antimeridian** is the meridian 180° both east and west of the prime meridian in a geographical coordinate system.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] The longitude at this line can be given as either east or west.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] On Earth, the prime and 180th meridians form a great ellipse that divides the planet into the Western and Eastern Hemispheres.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] The antimeridian passes mostly through the open waters of the Pacific Ocean but also runs across land in Russia, Fiji, and Antarctica.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] An important function of this meridian is its use as the basis for the International Date Line, which snakes around national borders to maintain date consistency within the territories of Russia, the United States, Kiribati, Fiji and New Zealand.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] The only places where roads cross this meridian are in Fiji and Russia.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] Fiji has several such roads and some buildings very close to it.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] Russia has three roads in the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] Many geographic software libraries or data formats project the world to a rectangle; very often this rectangle is split exactly at the 180th meridian.
[src:aleutian-islands/180th-meridian] This often makes it non-trivial to do simple tasks (like representing an area, or a line) over the 180th meridian.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The **1946 Aleutian Islands earthquake** occurred near the Aleutian Islands, Alaska on April 1, 1946.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] It had a maximum Mercalli intensity of VI (*Strong*).
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The seafloor along the fault was elevated, triggering a Pacific-wide tsunami with multiple destructive waves at heights ranging from 45–138 ft (14–42 m), resulting in 165–173 casualties and over US$26 million (equivalent to $429,000,000 in 2025) in damage.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The tsunami obliterated the Scotch Cap Lighthouse on Unimak Island, Alaska among others, and killed all five lighthouse keepers.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Despite the damage to the Aleutian Island Unimak, the tsunami had an almost imperceptible effect on the Alaskan mainland.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The Aleutian Islands are a group of 14 large and 55 smaller volcanic islands situated between mainland Alaska and Kamchatka.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] They are situated along the Aleutian Trench as they were formed by the active subduction of the oceanic Pacific plate underneath the continental crust of the North American plate.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The western portion of the trench becomes more and more oblique until near the Commander Islands where faulting becomes nearly exclusively strike-slip and causes earthquakes such as the 2017 Komandorski Islands earthquake.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The trench ends where the Kuril-Kamchatka Trench begins in the west.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] In the east, the trench extends for a couple of thousand miles before reaching the transition zone near Yakataga responsible for creating earthquakes such as the 1899 Yakutat Bay earthquakes.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The collision ends slightly further east, where the Queen Charlotte Fault becomes the dominant fault of the tectonic regime.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] This specific area of the Aleutian Islands is thought to have ruptured in the 1585 Aleutian Islands earthquake.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The earthquake struck at 02:29 local time on April 1, 1946, at a shallow depth of 15 km (9.3 mi).
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The earthquake was very large, but the maximum felt intensity was only a VI.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The earthquake was originally thought to be a rather smaller earthquake of Ms 7.4, however further research uncovered that this was truly a much larger event, but with a hidden seismic signature.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] A size of Mw 8.6 fits this event best, with an estimated slip between 9 m (30 ft) and 12.7 m (42 ft).
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] This event shows the classic signs of a tsunami earthquake as the surface-wave magnitude was very low compared to the moment and tsunami magnitudes, and the tsunami height was far larger than expected for the surface wave magnitude.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The very high tsunami magnitude value is due to the sheer strength of the waves.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] It was calculated by using tsunami run up from Honolulu, Hilo, and the average of stations in California.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Even excluding the values given by Hilo (the highest Mt), the tsunami magnitude is at least 9.1.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The earthquake was originally thought to be a strike-slip earthquake, and later a strike slip earthquake with a normal faulting component.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] These erroneous focal mechanisms were due to a lack of stations recording the earthquake.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] However, modeling of the S wave, rather than the P wave helped to uncover both the true magnitude of the earthquake, as well as the widely accepted thrusting mechanism.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] This thrust mechanism is consistent with a subduction earthquake helping to relieve stress on the Aleutian Trench.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] At Unimak Island, tsunami run-up reached 42 m (138 ft).
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The tsunami earthquake aspect of this event helps to explain a portion of this massive height; however, the rest must be attributed to a local submarine landslide.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Waves reportedly traveled across the ocean at 500 miles per hour (430 kn; 800 km/h) and measured 55 feet (17 m) high, crest to trough.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The wave reached Kauai, Hawaii 4.5 hours after the quake, and Hilo, Hawaii 4.9 hours after the event.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] In the Hawaiian Islands 159 people died.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] In Hilo alone, 96 people died, 163 were injured, 488 buildings were demolished and 936 more were damaged.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] On Kauai the McKee sugar mill and buildings were demolished, and the archives of the Kauai newspaper were a loss.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Witnesses told of waves inundating streets, homes, and storefronts.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Many victims were swept out to sea by receding water.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The tsunami caused much damage in Maui as well.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Waves there demolished 77 homes and many other buildings.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The residents of these islands were caught off-guard by the onset of the tsunami due to the inability to transmit warnings from the destroyed posts at Scotch Cap, and the tsunami is known as the April Fools' Day Tsunami in Hawaii because it happened on April 1.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The effects of the tsunami also reached Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The tsunami was unusually powerful for the size of the earthquake.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The event was classified as a tsunami earthquake due to the discrepancy between the size of the tsunami and the relatively low surface-wave magnitude.
[src:aleutian-islands/1946-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The large-scale destruction prompted the creation of the Seismic Sea Wave Warning System, which became known as the Pacific Tsunami Warning Center in 1965.
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The **2014 Aleutian Islands earthquake** occurred on 23 June at 11:53 HDT (UTC-9) with a moment magnitude of 7.9 and a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (*Severe*).
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The shock occurred in the Aleutian Islands – part of the US state of Alaska – 19 miles (31 km) southeast of Little Sitkin Island.
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The earthquake was initially reported as 8.0 Mw before it was downgraded to 7.9.
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The rupture was on a normal fault, at ~107 km depth.
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] Based on the geometry of the slab, and the relative movement of the tectonic plates, the slip vector is likely to have been oblique down-dip towards the ESE.
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] The fault plane appears to be oblique, striking NW-SE and cutting steeply into the subducting slab.
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] A tsunami warning was issued, but was soon downgraded to a tsunami advisory for much of the Aleutian Islands; however, the hypocenter was too deep to generate a tsunami that would affect the Pacific basin.
[src:aleutian-islands/2014-aleutian-islands-earthquake] A small non-destructive tsunami was generated, with heights of 17 cm on Amchitka.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The **2020 United States census** was the 24th decennial United States census.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Other than a pilot study during the 2000 census, this was the first U.S. census to offer options to respond online or by phone, in addition to the paper response form used for previous censuses.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The census was taken during the COVID-19 pandemic, which affected its administration.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The census recorded a resident population of 331,449,281 in the 50 states and the national capital of Washington, D.C., reflecting an increase of 7.4%, or 22,703,743, over 2010.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The growth rate was the second-lowest ever recorded, and the net increase was the sixth-highest in history.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] This was the first census where the ten most-populous states each surpassed ten million residents, and the first census where the ten most-populous cities each surpassed one million residents.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] This census's data determined the electoral votes' distribution for the 2024 United States presidential election.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S. census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The 2010 United States census was the previous census completed.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] 18 and older are legally obligated to answer census questions, and to do so truthfully (Title 13 of the United States Code).
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information is private and the Census Bureau itself will never release it.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] However, the National Archives and Records Administration could release the original census returns in 2092, if the 72-year rule is not changed before then.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On census reference day, April 1, 2020, the resident United States population (50 states and Washington, D.C., excluding overseas territories and military members and civilian U.S. citizens living abroad) was projected to be 329.59 million, a 6.76% increase from the 2010 census.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The results of the 2020 census determine the number of seats for each state in the House of Representatives, hence also the number of electors for each state in the Electoral College, for elections from 2022 to 2032.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Census Bureau announced the apportionment figures on April 26, 2021.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] This represented a smaller number of seats shifting than was forecast by independent analysts.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] State and local officials use censuses to redraw boundaries for districts such as congressional districts (redistricting), state legislative districts, and school districts.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Dozens of federal programs use census data to help direct funding to state and local areas.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census results help determine how more than $675 billion in federal funding are allocated to states and communities each year for roads, schools, hospitals (health clinics), emergency services, and more.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The 2020 census was the first U.S. census to offer a full internet response option and the first to extensively use technology instead of paper to manage and conduct fieldwork.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau submitted a list of questions to Congress on March 29, 2018.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The U.S. census will not share any participant's information with any government agency, as it is prohibited by Title 13 United States code.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] It has been challenged, but the Supreme Court has always prevailed in reference to Title 13 to protect the confidentiality and privacy of information provided.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Used to produce statistics about homeownership and renters for economic indicators, housing programs and informing planning decisions.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The sex of each person in the household.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Used to produce statistics used to plan and fund government programs, enforce laws, regulations, and policies against discrimination.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The age of each person in the household.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Used to better understand the size and characteristics of different age groups.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Agencies use these data to plan and fund government programs that support specific age groups, including children and older populations.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The race of each person in the household.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Used by federal agencies to monitor compliance with anti-discrimination provisions, such as those under the Voting Rights Act and the Civil Rights Act.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Whether a person in the household is of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The relationship of each person in the household to each other.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Used to plan and fund government programs that support families, including people raising children alone and other households who qualify for additional assistance.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The United States Census Bureau proposed but then withdrew plans to add a new category to classify Middle Eastern and North African peoples, over a dispute over whether this classification should be considered a white ethnicity or a separate race.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] According to the Census Bureau, 60.0% of all U.S. households had submitted their census questionnaire by May 22, 2020 –either online, by mail or by phone.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Most U.S. households were mailed an invitation letter between March 12–20 to self-respond.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] They account for more than 95% of all U.S. households.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Prior to the ongoing coronavirus pandemic, the remaining 5% of U.S. households (mostly in rural areas) were supposed to be visited by census takers in April/May, dropping off invitation letters to owners.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] This was delayed, but most census offices restarted work again in mid-May.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] In an update published October 19, 2020, the Census Bureau stated 99.98% of addresses had been accounted for, with all but one state over a 99.9% rate.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Paper responses postmarked on or before October 15 would be processed, as long as they arrived at the processing center by October 22.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] As in previous censuses, the 2020 census relied on a network of trusted voices nationwide to help raise awareness, answer questions, and encourage communities to participate.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Hundreds of local "complete count committees" are dedicating resources to the efforts nationwide.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] VMLY&R (formerly Young & Rubicam) secured the Integrated Communications Contract for the 2020 census campaign in August 2016.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] As the contract's primary agency of record, VMLY&R created an integrated team for this project, Team Y&R, which includes subcontractors specializing in minority outreach, digital media, earned media and more.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] In March 2019, the campaign unveiled the 2020 census tagline: "Shape your future.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] START HERE." The tagline was based on research that demonstrated which types of messages will reach and motivate all populations, including segments of the population who are historically hard to count.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The printing company Cenveo won the $61 million contract in October 2017 to produce census forms and reminders but went bankrupt less than four months later.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Government Publishing Office said the agency failed to check the company's financial status and improperly allowed the company to lower its bid after other bids were unsealed.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The coronavirus pandemic caused delays to census field operations and counts of the homeless and people living in group quarters.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] As of April 1, 2020, Census Day, the Census Bureau still planned to complete the count by the end of the year.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau issued a press release by Director Steven Dillingham announcing that 2020 census field operations would be suspended for two weeks until April 1, 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On March 27, 2020, the agency announced it would temporarily suspend in-person interviews for its on-going surveys.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The agency claimed that staffing adjustments at its call centers due to implementing health guidance had "led to increases in call wait times, affecting different languages at different times".
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] According to its own documentation, the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau continued to pay 2020 census employees even though field operations were supposed to be suspended.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau issued another press release announcing 2020 census field operations would be suspended for an additional two weeks, through April 15, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The agency announced on April 10, 2020, that it took steps to make "more employees available to respond to requests" at the call centers.
