[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Steven Dillingham announced further operational adjustments to the 2020 census due to COVID-19 health and safety concerns.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Steven Dillingham wrote to Department of Commerce inspector general Peggy E.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Gustafson responding to a March 12, 2020, memo sent by the Office of the Inspector General requesting information about the Census Bureau's plans to respond to the COVID-19 emergency by March 20, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The inspector general's memo asked how the Bureau would address staff and enumerator safety.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] To ensure the completeness and accuracy of the 2020 census, the Census Bureau is seeking statutory relief from Congress of 120 additional calendar days to deliver final apportionment counts.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On April 24, 2020, Dillingham and other Census Bureau officials briefed the House Committee on Oversight and Reform on the agency's response to the COVID-19 emergency.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] This briefing came after many requests from the committee since March 12, 2020, including a last-minute cancellation on April 20, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] However, the National Processing Center and Area Census Offices had remained open.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau began publishing dates as it claimed to begin a "phased restart of some 2020 census field operations in select geographic areas" and said they had "ordered personal protective equipment (PPE) for all field staff, including those that work in a field office.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The agency decided that face shields were necessary to protect employees from COVID-19 exposure, but provided them only to personnel at the headquarters and national processing centers.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Additional "restart" dates starting May 18 were published on May 15, 2020, for other geographic areas in eleven states.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] An OSHA complaint was recorded that same day from St.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Louis, that desks remained close together with no physical dividers, improper sanitation practices were being used, and no remote work for high-risk employees.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Louis Area Census Office was May 11, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On May 21, 2020, procurement information for two contracts was entered into the Federal Procurement Data System.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] A press release on May 22, 2020, announced May 25 "restart" dates for ten more states.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] An OSHA complaint was made from Concord, California, on April 3, 2020, that there were at least two confirmed cases of COVID-19 unrecorded on OSHA 300 logs and that employees were working in close quarters with no disinfection of shared equipment such as headsets, laptops, and tablets.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The published restart date for the Concord, California, Area Census Office was May 25, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Offices were reopened in the areas of "American Samoa, the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, Guam and the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Virgin Islands in preparation for resuming operations for the 2020 Island Areas Censuses" on May 22, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On May 29, 2020, a press release was published announcing "restart" of operations in seven additional states and the Washington, D.C., area starting from the week of June 1.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] In a June 5, 2020, press release, the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Days later, the Navajo Nation began reinstating lockdown restrictions and curfews due to a surge in new cases.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] A June 12, 2020, press release shared that the update leave (UL) operation had resumed, as well as fingerprinting of selected applicants.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On August 3, 2020, the Census Bureau announced that field collection would end on September 30, rather than October 31 as planned in April.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Zabarsky, Principal Assistant Inspector General for Audit and Evaluation published an alert on behalf of the Department of Commerce Office of Inspector General, which stated that the number of COVID-19 related safety issues raised by hotline complaints tripled between July 1 and August 21.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The U.S. decennial census is used to determine federal funds, grants, and support to states.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Census Bureau had included a citizenship question until 1950 when it was removed, though it continued to include a question asking about place of birth.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Ross was accused by Democrats in Congress of lying that the citizenship question was requested by the Justice Department and approved by him.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Upon the bureau's announcement, several state and city officials criticized the decision, reiterating the concern about discouraging participation from immigrants, resulting in undercounting, and questioning the motives of Secretary Ross in adding the question.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Three simultaneous separate federal lawsuits came out of this discovery, occurring at the district courts of New York, Maryland, and California.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] During these trials, documents released in May 2019 showed that the late Thomas B.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Hofeller, an architect of Republican gerrymandering, had found that adding the census question could help to gerrymander maps that "would be advantageous to Republicans and non-Hispanic whites".
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Hofeller later wrote the DOJ letter which justified the policy by claiming it was needed to enforce the 1965 Voting Rights Act.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration on June 12, 2019, asserted executive privilege over portions of the requested documents.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] As a result, the House committee subsequently voted along party lines to hold both Ross and Barr in contempt that day.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The full House voted to hold Ross and Barr in contempt on July 17, 2019, in a 230–198 vote along party lines.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] A lawsuit, led by New York state's attorney general Barbara Underwood and joined by seventeen other states, fifteen cities and other civil rights groups, was filed in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] During the discovery phase of the trial, new information came to light that Ross had had previous discussions with Steve Bannon before March 2018 with the intent to add the citizenship question, contradicting statements he had made to Congress in March.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Furman in September 2018 to ask that Ross clear a day in his schedule to give a deposition to the court related to the addition of the census question prior to the planned start of the trial in November.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration filed a writ of *mandamus* to the United States Supreme Court, requesting that they postpone the trial, and also to defer any involvement with Ross until the start of the trial.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court issued an order that allowed the trial *United States Census Bureau v.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] State of New York* to go forward, but agreed to postpone Ross's deposition until after the start of the trial.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court accepted the petition related to Furman's ruling on February 15, 2019, a separate matter from the question of Ross's deposition, and the case's oral arguments were heard on April 23, 2019.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court issued its decision on June 27, 2019, rejecting the Trump administration's stated rationale for including the question.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] While the Court majority agreed that the question was allowable under the Enumeration Act, they also agreed with the ability of the District Court to ask Commerce for further explanation for the question under the Administrative Procedure Act (APA).
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] They also agreed that the answers Commerce had provided at the time appeared to be "contrived" and pretextual, leaving open the possibility that Commerce could offer a better rationale.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The case was remanded back to the District Court, to allow Commerce to provide a better explanation for the rationale of the question to the District Court, who would deem if that was sufficient before allowing the question on the census.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The question would be allowed on the census only if these steps can be completed before the self-imposed form printing deadline.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) has taken steps to introduce the Hofeller evidence into the New York case but it will not be heard until late 2019 after the census forms are to be published.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The second suit over the census question came in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California under Judge Richard Seeborg, raised by the state of California and several cities within it.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] In March 2019, Seeborg similarly found as Furman had in New York that the addition of the census question was unconstitutional and issued an injunction to block its use.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The government appealed to the Ninth Circuit before the Supreme Court remanded the case.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] A similar question related to the intent of the question was raised by several immigrants-rights groups in the United States District Court for the District of Maryland.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The case was overseen by Judge George J.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Hazel had found for the pro-immigration groups in April 2019, ruling that the addition of an immigration question to the census was unconstitutional.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The government issued its appeal to the Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The new Hofeller evidence was presented to Hazel as the case was being heard on appeal during June 2019 at the Fourth Circuit.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Hazel said the new evidence "raises a substantial issue".
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On June 25, 2019, the Fourth Circuit remanded the case back to Hazel's District Court with the newly provided evidence, and to review if the additional evidence showed discriminatory intent.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Should Hazel find such intent, it would be possible for him to place an injunction on the addition of the census question during a new discovery phase, regardless of the Supreme Court decision in *Department of Commerce v.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] This action would effectively render the question moot since the census forms would need to be published at this point without the citizenship question to meet the mailing deadlines.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] President Trump, after the Supreme Court decision in *Department of Commerce* was announced, stated his intent to find a way to delay the census as long as possible so the judicial matter could be resolved.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On July 2, 2019, the Department of Justice (DOJ) announced that the citizenship question would not be included in the census, and the Commerce Department began printing census forms without a citizenship question.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] However, the next day, Trump insisted his administration was "absolutely moving forward" with the citizenship question, and the Justice Department confirmed in court that it had been instructed to find a legal way to include it in the census.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] In response to an order from Judge Hazel, the Justice Department affirmed on July 5, 2019, that it will be seeking a route to add the citizenship question to the census, though at the time did not know which route it would take.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Hazel had ordered this response as, if the department was intending to add the question, he could begin determining a schedule in coordination with Judge Furman in the New York court for further proceedings and discovery in both the New York and the Maryland lawsuits.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Furman pointed out that the case had already run past the DOJ's own previously requested deadline of July 1 and replacing counsel would cause further delays.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Separate from the events in the courts, Trump has said he also considered using an executive order to place the citizenship question on the census.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] However, on July 11 he issued Executive Order 13880 directing the Department of Commerce to obtain citizenship data from other federal agencies rather than via the census.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] He added that "we are not backing down in our effort to determine the citizenship status of the United States population" and that data from other federal agencies would be "far more accurate" than a census question.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Accordingly, the department will promptly inform the courts that the government will not include a citizenship question on the 2020 decennial census." Besides federal agencies, the Department of Commerce is obtaining citizenship data from state records.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Joe Biden, on his first day of his presidency on January 20, 2021, issued an executive order that revoked both Trump's July 11 executive order and Trump's July 21 memo, as to have the census follow the standard practice of including the counts of undocumented immigrants within the final numbers.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The order did not rescind a directive for the Census Bureau to use government records to produce block-level citizenship data.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The state believed it would lose a congressional seat to other states that have had increased numbers of immigrants in the last decade.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The motion was granted by the end of 2018.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] As the census question case continued, the Census Bureau spoke of other means to obtain immigration data, and Barr, referencing the Alabama suit, said that "for example, there is a current dispute over whether illegal aliens can be included for apportionment purposes.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Depending on the resolution of that dispute, this data may be relevant to those considerations.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] We will be studying this issue." Spurred by Barr's comments that the government would not defend itself in the case, a coalition of fifteen states and other groups also moved to intervene, which was granted by September 2019.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On July 21, 2020, President Trump signed a memo to the Department of Commerce, "Memorandum on Excluding Illegal Aliens from the Apportionment Base Following the 2020 Census" with instructions not to include illegal immigrants in the census totals for purposes of apportionment.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The memo said the Constitution does not define which "persons" must be included in the apportionment base, and past censuses have excluded some legal immigrants in the country temporarily, justifying the change.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Law and census experts said this was an invalid interpretation as past case law has supported inclusion of "whole persons" including illegal immigrants, and the ACLU immediately said they planned to file a lawsuit against the administration over the memo.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Common Cause, the city of Atlanta, and other groups and individuals filed the first suit seeking an injunction to prevent the government from executing on the memo a week after it was signed in the United States District Court for the District of Columbia.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On September 10, 2020, a three-judge panel of the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York unanimously rejected the order, ruling that it was so obviously illegal a lawsuit challenging it was unnecessary.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Eight days later, the Trump administration filed notice that it would appeal the decision directly to the Supreme Court, bypassing the circuit court appeals process.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court accepted the petition on October 16, 2020, and scheduled expedited oral arguments in the case on November 30, 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Court ruled in a *per curiam* decision on December 18, 2020, that the case was premature due to lack of standing and ripeness but did not rule on any of the constitutional challenges at the time.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The decision vacated the District Court's ruling and remanded the case to the District Court to be dismissed.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration sought to complete the census count earlier than originally scheduled.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] In September 2020, federal district court judge Lucy Koh issued a preliminary injunction against the plan to end counting on September 30 rather than the scheduled October 31, saying the Commerce Department "never articulated a satisfactory explanation".
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] She also blocked a plan to deliver the count results to the White House by December 31, rather than the original April 2021 delivery date when Trump might be out of office.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On the next business day, Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross announced the count would end October 5, as the administration appealed Koh's decision to the ninth circuit.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Koh ordered the government to produce documents to show the Commerce Department's reasoning.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The appeals court upheld Koh's ruling, and the Census Bureau announced on October 2 that the count would continue until October 31.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Also on October 2, Koh threatened to hold Ross in contempt for repeated violations of her order.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The ninth circuit decision was appealed to the Supreme Court.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On October 13, in a 7–1 ruling, the court issued an unsigned order granting the request to end the count early.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] As one of his first acts in office, President Joe Biden signed Executive Order 13986 on January 20, 2021, to discontinue citizenship tabulations at the city-block level using 2020 census data with administrative records.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] He also revoked a Trump directive that would have excluded those in the country illegally from the figures used for apportioning congressional seats among the states.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Researchers widely criticized the Census Bureau for intentionally making block-level data inaccurate by using differential privacy.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] In order to purportedly prevent identification of individuals' age, gender, race, household relationships, or homeownership, "disclosure avoidance noise" was added to the data, shifting individuals between blocks, towns, or other units.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] This can result in substantial discrepancies in minority populations and the sizes of small places.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] For example, Monowi, Nebraska, known for being the country's smallest incorporated municipality, was incorrectly reported to have two residents instead of one.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Redistricting data would also be corrupted, making equal-size districts and majority-minority districts more difficult.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] On March 10, 2022, the Census Bureau released estimates of total overcount and undercount by demographic characteristic.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] The results found that the total Hispanic population had likely been undercounted by 4.99%, the Black population by 3.3% and *Some other race* by 4.34%.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Asians were estimated to have been overcounted by 2.62%, Non-Hispanic Whites by 1.64%, and Pacific Islanders by 1.28%.
[src:aleutian-islands/2020-united-states-census] Native Americans were estimated to have been undercounted by 0.91%; however, those living on reservations were undercounted by 5.64%, while those living elsewhere were overcounted by 3.06%.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] The number of abortion clinics in Alaska has been declining, going from fourteen in 1982 to thirteen in 1992 to three in 2014.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] 1,547 abortions took place in Alaska in 2014, and 1,459 took place in 2015.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] There is state funding for abortions based on income.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska, California, and New Hampshire did not voluntarily provide the Center for Disease Control with abortion related data in 2000 or 2001.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2014, a poll by the Pew Research Center reported that 63% of adults in the state of Alaska believe abortion should be legal in all or most cases, with 34% stating it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska, Hawaii, Washington, and New York were the only four states that made abortion legal between 1967 and 1970 that did not require a reason to request an abortion.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 1970, the state repealed some of its abortion laws, along with Hawaii, New York, and Washington.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] The following year, Alaska repealed its statute that said inducing an abortion was a criminal offense.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] State law still required in 1971 that any woman getting a legal abortion in the state needed to be a resident for some specific period between 30 and 90 days.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Some states, such as Alaska, Mississippi, West Virginia, Texas, and Kansas, have passed laws requiring abortion providers to warn patients of a link between abortion and breast cancer, and to issue other scientifically unsupported warnings.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] The state was one of 23 states in 2007 to have a detailed abortion-specific informed consent requirement.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska and Minnesota both require that women seeking abortions after 20 weeks be informed that, while experts disagree on the issue of whether or not a fetus can feel pain at 20 weeks, it is possible.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] House Bill 250 was introduced in 2017 by Rep.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] The bill was called the "Life at Conception Act", and it never made it out of committee in Alaska's House.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2017, Washington State, New Mexico, Illinois, Alaska, Maryland, Massachusetts, Connecticut, and New Jersey allow, by state law qualified non-physicians to prescribe drugs for medical abortions only.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In May 2019, Eastman introduced House Bill 178, which defines abortion as "murder of an unborn child"; the bill was never heard before a committee.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2022, Governor Mike Dunleavy expressed interest in an amendment to the Alaska Constitution clarifying the legality of abortion in the state.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] 2022 happened to be the year that Alaska's regularly scheduled ballot question for calling a state constitutional convention was asked.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Dunleavy and other anti-abortion advocates recommended voting "yes", but the question was resoundingly defeated, with 70% voting "no".
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2023, the bipartisan coalition majority in the Alaska State Senate is consensus-focused and unlikely to address controversial topics like abortion.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] The US Supreme Court's decision in 1973's *Roe v.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Wade* ruling meant the state could no longer regulate abortion in the first trimester.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 1997, the Alaska Supreme Court ruled in *Valley Hospital Association, Inc. v.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Mat-Su Coalition for Choice* that the privacy clause of the Alaska Constitution protects the right to an abortion.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] This ruling remains in effect after the US Supreme Court overruled Roe v.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2016, the Alaska Supreme Court struck down a parental notification law that had been established in 2010.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In September 2024, an Alaska superior court judge struck down the requirement that only licensed physicians provide abortions, meaning that the procedure can now also be legally performed by nurse practitioners and physician assistants.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Between 1982 and 1992, the number of abortion clinics in the state decreased by 1, going from 14 in 1982 to 13 in 1992.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2014, there were 3 abortion clinics in the state.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] 90% of the boroughs in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] That year, 37% of women in the state aged 15–44 lived in a borough without an abortion clinic.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In March 2016, there were 4 Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] There were still 4 Planned Parenthood clinics the following year, all of which offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 167,815 women aged 15–49.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2022, there were three Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2024, there were two Planned Parenthood clinics.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 1990, 69,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2013, among white women aged 15–19, there were 130 abortions, 10 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 20 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 70 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2017, the state had an infant mortality rate of 5.6 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] 17 US states, including Alaska, use their own funds to cover all or most "medically necessary" abortions sought by low-income women under Medicaid, 13 of which are required by State court orders to do so.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] In 2010, the state had 835 publicly funded abortions, all of which were state funded.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Women from the state participated in marches supporting abortion rights as part of a #StoptheBans movement in May 2019.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Hundreds of women attended a rally in Anchorage at Town Square Park to protest legislation proposed in Alaska's House to restrict abortion rights.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] The event was organized by Planned Parenthood Votes and Alaska ACLU.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] There was another rally at the Alaska Capitol in Juneau in May 2019, in opposition to the bill proposed by Republican Rep.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Following the leak of the overturning of Roe v.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] Wade on May 2, 2022, Alaska saw abortion rights protests in Anchorage, Fairbanks, and Haines.
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] David Eastman (R-Wasilla) was censured by the Alaska Legislature in 2017 after he claimed that women used Medicaid support for abortion as a "free trip to the city".
[src:aleutian-islands/abortion-in-alaska] A small counter-protest was organized by anti-abortion rights activists at the Alaska Capitol in Juneau in May 2019, in support of proposed restrictions on women's ability to access legal abortions in the state.
[src:aleutian-islands/abya-yala] The first explicit usage of the expression in its political sense was at the 2nd Continental Summit of Indigenous Peoples and Nationalities of Abya Yala, held in Quito in 2004.
[src:aleutian-islands/abya-yala] The symbolic and ideological significance of this summit is reflected in its rejection of neoliberal globalization, its reaffirmation of Indigenous peoples' rights to territorial autonomy, and its continuity with the earlier declarations made at the 2000 Teotihuacan Summit.
[src:aleutian-islands/abya-yala] Many Indigenous movements have adopted this designation to replace colonial names such as ‘Latin America’ to express a connection to the land, community and ancestral memory.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] Unlike the rest of the Chontal Maya region, cacao (although present) was not produced in economically significant quantities in Acalan, though its merchants still played the role of middlemen in its distribution.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] More prominent products included gold, cotton, and honey.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] Much of the nobility had Nahuatl names, indicating either an ethnic Nahua presence or the use of Nahuatl as a trade language.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] Acalan was governed as a sort of merchant republic, where the most influential merchant became the ruler though his power was checked by councils of merchants representing the four wards of the capital.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] Acalan also maintained a trade post at Nito in Guatemala.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] The ruler's patron deity was Kukulkan, called *Kukulchan* in Chontal.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] The four quarters of the town had their own patron deities, namely Ix Chel (patron of weaving, women, and childbirth), Ikchaua (patron of cacao and merchants), Tabay (patron of hunters), and Cabtanilcab.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] Ix Chel was especially important, and maidens were raised with the express purpose of being sacrificed to her.
[src:aleutian-islands/acalan] Cuauhtemoc, ruler of Tenochtitlan, capital of the Aztec Empire, was executed by Hernán Cortés while they were stopped in the Acalan capital of Itzamkanac (modern El Tigre on the right bank of the Candelaria River) in 1525.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Most of the islands belong to the U.S. state of Alaska, with the archipelago encompassing the Aleutians West Census Area and the Aleutians East Borough.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Commander Islands, located further to the west, belong to the Russian federal subject of Kamchatka Krai, of the Russian Far East.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Crossing longitude 180°, at which point east and west longitude end, the archipelago contains both the westernmost and easternmost parts of the United States, by longitude (Amatignak Island and Semisopochnoi Island, respectively).
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The westernmost U.S. island, in real terms, however, is Attu Island, west of which runs the International Date Line.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The islands, with their 57 volcanoes, form the northernmost part of the Pacific Ring of Fire.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Physiographically, they are a distinct section of the larger Pacific Border province, which, in turn, is part of the larger Pacific Mountain System physiographic division.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The islands are considered to be among the most geographically isolated areas of the Northern Pacific.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Battles and skirmishes took place during the Aleutian Islands campaign of World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Japanese landing and occupations of Kiska and Attu, in June 1942, were one of only two invasions of the United States in North America during WWII; the Philippines, Guam and Wake Atoll, Pacific territories of the United States, were also invaded.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Motion between the Kula Plate and the North American Plate along the margin of the Bering Shelf (in the Bering Sea north of the Aleutian arc) ended in the early Eocene.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian Basin, the ocean floor north of the Aleutian arc, is the remainder of the Kula Plate that was trapped when volcanism and subduction jumped south to its current location at c.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian island arc formed in the Early Eocene (55–50 Ma) when the subduction of the Pacific Plate under the North American Plate began.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The arc is made of separate blocks that have been rotated clockwise.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The basement underlying the islands is made of three stratigraphic units: an Eocene layer of volcanic rock, an Oligocene–Miocene layer of marine sedimentary rock, and a Pliocene–Quaternary layer of sedimentary and igneous rock.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] All six are located between 51° and 55° N latitude and 172° E and 163° W longitude.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The largest islands in the Aleutians are Attu, and Unalaska, Umnak, and Unimak in the Fox Islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The largest of those is Unimak Island, with an area of 1,571.41 mi2 (4,069.9 km2), followed by Unalaska Island, the only other Aleutian Island with an area over 1,000 square miles (2,600 km2).
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The axis of the archipelago near the mainland of Alaska has a southwest trend, but at Tanaga Island (about 178° W) its direction changes to the northwest.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] This change of direction corresponds to a curve in the line of volcanic fissures that have contributed their products to the building of the islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Such curved chains are repeated about the Pacific Ocean in the Kuril Islands, the Japanese chain, and in the Philippines.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] All these island arcs are at the edge of the Pacific Plate and experience much seismic activity, but are still habitable; the Aleutians lie between the Pacific and North American tectonic plates.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The general elevation is greatest in the eastern islands and least in the western.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The island chain is a western continuation of the Aleutian Range on the mainland.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The great majority of the islands bear evident marks of volcanic origin, and there are numerous volcanic cones on the north side of the chain, some of them active; many of the islands, however, are not wholly volcanic, but contain crystalline or sedimentary rocks, and also amber and beds of lignite.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The coasts are rocky and surf-worn, and the approaches are exceedingly dangerous, the land rising immediately from the coasts to steep, bold mountains.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] These volcanic islands reach heights of 6,200 feet (1,900 m).
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Makushin Volcano (5,691 feet (1,735 m)) on Unalaska Island, is not quite visible from within the town of Unalaska, though the steam rising from its cone is visible on a (rare) clear day.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Residents of Unalaska need only to climb one of the smaller hills in the area, such as Pyramid Peak or Mt.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Newhall, to get a good look at the snow-covered cone.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The volcanic Bogoslof and Fire Islands, which rose from the sea in 1796 and 1883 respectively, lie about 30 miles (50 km) west of Unalaska Bay.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In 1906, a new volcanic cone rose between the islets of Bogoslof and Grewingk, near Unalaska, followed by another in 1907.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] These cones were nearly demolished by an explosive eruption on September 1, 1907.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In 2017, the volcanic cone erupted sending ash and ice particles 30,000 feet (9000 m) into the air.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Alfred Russel Wallace's 1879 book *Australasia*, Ian Todd's 1974 book *Island Realm: A Pacific Panorama* and Dean Kohlhoff's 2002 book *Amchitka and the Bomb: Nuclear Testing in Alaska* all associate the Aleutian Islands with the Oceania region due to their status as remote islands in the Pacific.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The islands, having biogeographical and ethnocultural affinities to North America, are not ordinarily considered a part of the region.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The climate of the islands is oceanic, with moderate and fairly uniform temperatures and heavy rainfall.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Summer weather is much cooler than Southeast Alaska (around Sitka), but the winter temperature of the islands and of the Alaska Panhandle is nearly the same.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] To the northeast of that point, the climate becomes "Subarctic With Cool Summers And Year Around Rainfall" (type "Dfc", like Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky, Murmansk, St.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Moritz, and Labrador City), where it is similar albeit colder, with the coldest month averaging below 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] During the winter, the islands become the center of a semi-permanent low-pressure area called the Aleutian Low.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The mean annual temperature for Unalaska, the most populated island of the group, is about 38 °F (3 °C), being about 30 °F (−1 °C) in January and about 52 °F (11 °C) in August.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The highest and lowest temperatures recorded on the islands were 78 °F (26 °C) and 5 °F (−15 °C), respectively.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The average amount of annual rainfall is about 80 inches (2,000 mm); Unalaska, with about 250 rainy days per year, is said to be one of the rainiest places within the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The growing season lasts approximately 135 days, from early in May until late in September, but agriculture is limited to the raising of few vegetables.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] With the exception of some stunted willows, the vast majority of the chain is devoid of native trees.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] On some of the islands, such as Adak and Amaknak, there are a few coniferous trees growing, remnants of the Russian period.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] While tall trees grow in many cold climates, Aleutian conifers — some estimated to be two hundred years old — rarely reach a height of even 10 feet (3 m), and many of them are still less than 5 feet (1.5 m) tall.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] This is because the islands, much like the Falklands and other islands of similar latitudes, experience such strong winds that taller trees are vulnerable to snapping off.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Instead of trees, the islands are covered with a luxuriant, dense growth of herbage and shrubs, including crowberry, bluejoint, grasses, sedges, and many flowering plants.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] There are areas of peat bog near the coasts.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Endemic plants include the endangered Aleutian shield fern.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] There is currently almost no naturally occurring forest in the Aleutian Islands, except with the help of human intervention.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] For example, the “Adak National Forest” on Adak Island is a man-made tree group consisting of 33 trees.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleutians are home to many large colonies of seabirds.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Buldir Island has 21 breeding seabird species, including the Bering Sea-endemic red-legged kittiwake.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Large seabird colonies are also present at Kiska, Gareloi, Semisopochnoi, Bogoslof, and others.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The islands are also frequented by vagrant Asiatic birds, including the common rosefinch, Siberian rubythroat, bluethroat, lanceolated warbler, and the first North American record of the intermediate egret.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The habitats of the Aleutians are largely unspoiled, but wildlife is affected by competition from introduced species such as cattle, caribou, and foxes.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Nearly all of the Aleutians are protected as part of the Alaska Maritime National Wildlife Refuge and the Aleutian Islands Wilderness.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Observations have identified sea otters as a keystone species along the coasts of many of the Aleutian Islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Their presence encourages the growth of kelp forests, as the otters control sea urchin populations (as large populations of sea urchins can create urchin barrens by clearing away kelp stands).
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The native people refer to themselves as Unangan, and are now generally known by most non-natives as the Aleut.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleut language is one of the two main branches of the Eskimo–Aleut language family.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] This family is not known to be related to any others.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The 2020 U.S. census recorded a population of 7,152 on the islands, of whom 4,254 were living in the main settlement of Unalaska.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] On the less mountainous islands, the raising of sheep and reindeer was once believed to be practicable.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] There are bison on islands near Sand Point.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Sheep raising seems to have died off with the advent of synthetic fibers, which lowered the value of wool.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] During the 1980s, there were some llama being raised on Unalaska.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The current economy is primarily based on fishing, and the presence of U.S. military.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Chickens are raised in barns under protection from the cold.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In addition to a partial air service and a ferry service, the Alaska Marine Highway passes through many of the U.S. islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Because the islands stretch like a broken bridge from the continent Asia to the continent North America, many anthropologists hypothesize they were a route of the first human occupants of the Americas.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] However, the earliest known evidence in public recorded history of human occupation in the Americas is found much farther south.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The early human sites in the Bering Sea were probably submerged by rising waters and sand during the current interglacial period.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] People living in or on the Aleutian Islands developed skills in hunting, fishing, and basketry.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The baskets were woven with shredded stalks of beach rye.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Explorers, traders and missionaries arrived from Russia beginning in 1741.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In 1741 the Russian government sent Vitus Bering, a Danish-born Russian, and Aleksei Chirikov, a Russian, in the ships *Saint Peter* and *Saint Paul* on a voyage of discovery in the Northern Pacific.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] After the ships were separated by a storm; Chirikov discovered several eastern islands of the Aleutian group, and Bering discovered several of the western islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Bering was shipwrecked and died in the Komandorski Islands (Commander Islands); one of which now bears his name (Bering Island), along with the surrounding Bering Sea.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The survivors of Bering's party reached the Kamchatka Peninsula in a boat constructed from the wreckage of their ship, and reported the islands were rich in fur-bearing animals.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Siberian fur hunters flocked to the Commander Islands and gradually moved eastward across the Aleutian Islands to North America.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In this manner, Russia gained a foothold on the northwestern coast of North America.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian Islands consequently belonged to Russia, until that country transferred all its possessions in North America to the U.S. in the 1867 Alaska Purchase.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The colonies soon entered a relatively stable state based on cooperation, intermarriage, and official policies that provided social status, education, and professional training to children of mixed Aleut-Russian birth.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Within a generation, the day-to-day administration of the Russian-American colonies was largely in the hands of native-born Alaskans.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Reversing the usual trend in colonization where indigenous technologies are replaced, the Russians adopted the Aleut kayak, or baidarka, sea otter hunting techniques, and the working of native copper deposits.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] By 1760 the Russian merchant Andrian Tolstykh had made a detailed census in the vicinity of Adak and extended Russian citizenship to the Aleuts.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] During his third and last voyage in 1778, Captain James Cook surveyed the eastern portion of the Aleutian archipelago, accurately determined the position of some of the more important islands, and corrected many errors of former navigators.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Among the first Christian missionaries to arrive in the Aleutian Islands was a party of ten Russian Orthodox monks and priests, who arrived in 1793.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Within two years, a monk named Herman was the only survivor of that party.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] He settled on Spruce Island, near Kodiak Island, and often defended the rights of the Aleuts against the Russian trading companies.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] He is now known in the Orthodox Church as Saint Herman of Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Another early Christian missionary of the Russian Orthodox Church was Father Veniaminov who arrived in Unalaska in 1824.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] He was named Bishop Innokentii in 1840 and moved to Sitka.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] He is now known in the Orthodox Church as Saint Innocent of Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The principal settlements were on Unalaska Island.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The oldest was Iliuliuk (also called Unalaska), settled in 1760–1775, with a customs house and an Orthodox church.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] After the American purchase of Alaska from Russia in 1867, further development took place.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] New buildings included a Methodist mission and orphanage, and the headquarters for a considerable fleet of United States revenue cutters, which patrolled the sealing grounds of the Pribilof Islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The first public school in Unalaska opened in 1883.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Congress extended American citizenship to all Native Americans in 1924; this law has been held to include the indigenous peoples of Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] A hospital was built in Unalaska in 1933 by the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] Navy, having broken the Japanese naval codes, proceeded as if this was just a diversion, and it did not expend large amounts of effort in defending the islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] More than 90 Americans were taken to Japan as prisoners of war.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The United States moved most of the remaining civilian population (over 800) of the Aleutians and Pribilovians to camps in the Alaska Panhandle.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In May 1943, American forces invaded Japanese-held Attu and defeated the Japanese.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In August 1943, American and Canadian troops launched an invasion of Kiska, in which 34,426 men composed of both Americans and Canadian participated; however, Japanese forces had already evacuated the island, ending the campaign in the islands.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] President Roosevelt visited Adak in 1944, meeting with commanders and eating with soldiers of the garrison.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] This was his first and only trip to the Aleutian Islands and Alaska as a whole.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] A rumor spread that FDR had accidentally left his Scottish Terrier "Fala" on one of the Islands and had to send a destroyer to retrieve the dog, costing taxpayers several million dollars.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The President made fun of these rumors during a talk with the Teamsters Union in Washington DC, now known as the "Fala Speech".
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] June 3, 2002, was celebrated as Dutch Harbor Remembrance Day.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The governor of Alaska ordered state flags lowered to half-staff to honor the 43 Americans who died during the two-day Japanese air attack in 1942.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian World War II National Historic Area Visitors Center opened that month.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The U.S. conducted underground tests of nuclear weapons on Amchitka Island from 1965 to 1971 as part of the Vela Uniform program.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The final detonation, the Cannikin, was the largest underground nuclear explosion by the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act became law in 1971.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] In 1977, the Ounalashka Corporation (from Unalaska) declared a dividend.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] This was the first village corporation to declare and pay a dividend to its shareholders.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian Islands were designated a UNESCO biosphere reserve in 1976.
[src:aleutian-islands/aleutian-islands] The Aleutians were one of 17 biosphere reserves in the United States withdrawn by request of the U.S. government from the programme in June 2017.
